[
    {
        "content": "<p>Do we have a proof of the Blumberg theorem, which states that for every <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>f</mi><mo>:</mo><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">R</mi><mo>→</mo><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">R</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">f : \\mathbb{R} \\to \\mathbb{R}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8889em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10764em;\">f</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6889em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">R</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6889em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">R</span></span></span></span> there exists a dense subset <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>D</mi><mo>⊆</mo><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">R</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">D \\subseteq \\mathbb{R}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8193em;vertical-align:-0.136em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.02778em;\">D</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">⊆</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6889em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">R</span></span></span></span> such that the restriction <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>f</mi><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">∣</mi><mi>D</mi></msub><mo>:</mo><mi>D</mi><mo>→</mo><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">R</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">f|_D : D \\to \\mathbb{R}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10764em;\">f</span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\">∣</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3283em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:0em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.02778em;\">D</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.02778em;\">D</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6889em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">R</span></span></span></span> is continuous?</p>",
        "id": 510400526,
        "sender_full_name": "Niels Voss",
        "timestamp": 1743878950
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I didn't know the theorem before and it's quite interesting. I looked up Wikipedia and this is particularly interesting:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>It was constructed by taking the disjoint union of two compact Hausdorff spaces, one of which could be proven to be non-Blumberg if the <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Continuum_Hypothesis\">Continuum Hypothesis</a> was true, the other if it was false.</p>\n</blockquote>",
        "id": 510413236,
        "sender_full_name": "Junyan Xu",
        "timestamp": 1743887818
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>PDF of the original paper: <a href=\"https://www.ams.org/journals/tran/1922-024-02/S0002-9947-1922-1501216-9/S0002-9947-1922-1501216-9.pdf\">https://www.ams.org/journals/tran/1922-024-02/S0002-9947-1922-1501216-9/S0002-9947-1922-1501216-9.pdf</a></p>\n<p>Theorem III is the \"Blumberg theorem\" (though I suppose that they're all technically Blumberg theorems...)</p>",
        "id": 510414809,
        "sender_full_name": "Matt Diamond",
        "timestamp": 1743888980
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"224323\">Junyan Xu</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/217875-Is-there-code-for-X.3F/topic/Blumberg.20theorem/near/510413236\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>I didn't know the theorem before and it's quite interesting. I looked up Wikipedia and this is particularly interesting:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>It was constructed by taking the disjoint union of two compact Hausdorff spaces, one of which could be proven to be non-Blumberg if the <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Continuum_Hypothesis\">Continuum Hypothesis</a> was true, the other if it was false.</p>\n</blockquote>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Sounds like the proof relied on the law of excluded middle <span aria-label=\"rofl\" class=\"emoji emoji-1f923\" role=\"img\" title=\"rofl\">:rofl:</span></p>",
        "id": 510596667,
        "sender_full_name": "Johan Commelin",
        "timestamp": 1744014832
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I think that without LEM you might well have several competing definitions of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">R</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbb{R}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6889em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">R</span></span></span></span>...</p>",
        "id": 510602642,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Buzzard",
        "timestamp": 1744016294
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Would this counterexample of a Compact Hausdorff Space that is non-Blumberg be a good candidate for Mathlib Counterexamples?</p>",
        "id": 510759601,
        "sender_full_name": "Niels Voss",
        "timestamp": 1744056998
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Who knew that open subsets of the plane were called \"I-regions\" in 1919?!</p>",
        "id": 510760048,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Buzzard",
        "timestamp": 1744057173
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Theorem III does not state what the original post in this thread says; the D is a dense subset of the plane, not the line (so in fact I'm slightly confused; if D is the complement of the graph of f then Theorem III as stated in this 1919 paper seems vacuously true...)</p>",
        "id": 510764781,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Buzzard",
        "timestamp": 1744059119
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>This paper is much easier to read: <a href=\"https://www.ams.org/journals/proc/1960-011-04/S0002-9939-1960-0146310-1/S0002-9939-1960-0146310-1.pdf\">https://www.ams.org/journals/proc/1960-011-04/S0002-9939-1960-0146310-1/S0002-9939-1960-0146310-1.pdf</a> (it definitely looks formalizable, it's only 3 pages  and is almost entirely self-contained)</p>",
        "id": 510765225,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Buzzard",
        "timestamp": 1744059301
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"110038\">Kevin Buzzard</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/217875-Is-there-code-for-X.3F/topic/Blumberg.20theorem/near/510764781\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Theorem III does not state what the original post in this thread says; the D is a dense subset of the plane, not the line (so in fact I'm slightly confused; if D is the complement of the graph of f then Theorem III as stated in this 1919 paper seems vacuously true...)</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>I think in that particular theorem <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>f</mi><mo>:</mo><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">R</mi><mo>×</mo><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">R</mi><mo>→</mo><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">R</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">f:\\mathbb{R}\\times \\mathbb{R}\\to\\mathbb{R}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8889em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10764em;\">f</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7722em;vertical-align:-0.0833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">R</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">×</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6889em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">R</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6889em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">R</span></span></span></span></p>",
        "id": 510765620,
        "sender_full_name": "Mario Carneiro",
        "timestamp": 1744059478
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>and it seems the <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">R</mi><mo>×</mo><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">R</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbb{R}\\times\\mathbb{R}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7722em;vertical-align:-0.0833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">R</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">×</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6889em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">R</span></span></span></span> was later generalized to what we are now calling Blumberg's theorem</p>",
        "id": 510765797,
        "sender_full_name": "Mario Carneiro",
        "timestamp": 1744059555
    },
    {
        "content": "<blockquote>\n<p>This paper is much easier to read: <a href=\"https://www.ams.org/journals/proc/1960-011-04/S0002-9939-1960-0146310-1/S0002-9939-1960-0146310-1.pdf\">https://www.ams.org/journals/proc/1960-011-04/S0002-9939-1960-0146310-1/S0002-9939-1960-0146310-1.pdf</a> (it definitely looks formalizable, it's only 3 pages  and is almost entirely self-contained)</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>I think I looked at that earlier and it definitely seems simpler. The paper seems to create new definitions of a point being meager relative to a subset of a space, a space being of the \"homogenous second category\", the concept of a heavy point, and something called an almost continuous function</p>",
        "id": 510765979,
        "sender_full_name": "Niels Voss",
        "timestamp": 1744059629
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Do we have the definitions of first and second Baire category? (I really don't like those names...)</p>",
        "id": 510766346,
        "sender_full_name": "Mario Carneiro",
        "timestamp": 1744059796
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I think those are just meager and nonmeager, respectively?</p>",
        "id": 510766429,
        "sender_full_name": "Niels Voss",
        "timestamp": 1744059829
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>looks like the mathlib notion is <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=residual#doc\">docs#residual</a>, although I'm not sure exactly which terminologies it equates to</p>",
        "id": 510766927,
        "sender_full_name": "Mario Carneiro",
        "timestamp": 1744060031
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Oh, there is also <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=IsMeagre#doc\">docs#IsMeagre</a> and some spelling clash of \"meagre\" / \"meager\" in docstrings</p>",
        "id": 510767207,
        "sender_full_name": "Mario Carneiro",
        "timestamp": 1744060136
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Based on some quick wikipedia reading, I think residual == comeager, which means that the complement is meager. comeager is not the same as nonmeager. I think we have an IsMeager predicate somewhere in Mathlib?</p>",
        "id": 510767215,
        "sender_full_name": "Niels Voss",
        "timestamp": 1744060139
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Yeah that sounds right</p>",
        "id": 510767532,
        "sender_full_name": "Niels Voss",
        "timestamp": 1744060253
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Should I make a PR to change all 8 instances of \"meager\" in docstrings to \"meagre\"?</p>",
        "id": 510805321,
        "sender_full_name": "Niels Voss",
        "timestamp": 1744080560
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>should there generally be a preference for US vs UK spelling in mathlib? Seems like a dedicated discussion is in order</p>",
        "id": 510805484,
        "sender_full_name": "Mario Carneiro",
        "timestamp": 1744080665
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I'm glad the 8 \"misspellings\" were there or I wouldn't have found the definition at all</p>",
        "id": 510805558,
        "sender_full_name": "Mario Carneiro",
        "timestamp": 1744080714
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>all spellings should definitely be mentioned in the declaration docstring</p>",
        "id": 510805613,
        "sender_full_name": "Mario Carneiro",
        "timestamp": 1744080735
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Yeah, that sounds reasonable. The docstring  should also mention \"Baire first category\". There are 40 instances of \"meagre\" (based on the result of <code>rg meager --ignore-case -c</code>) and 8 instances of \"meager\". I actually initially used \"meager\" because I live in the US, but I think we should use the one that appears most often in math literature.</p>",
        "id": 510805859,
        "sender_full_name": "Niels Voss",
        "timestamp": 1744080920
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Agreed. ...Do we know which one that is?</p>",
        "id": 510807027,
